{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.19,0.01,0.53,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54335"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4080"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2021-12-16T10:21:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T23:39:38+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-05-13T20:48:34+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-25 11:40:38"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11446"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39843"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1490"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44678"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39843"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54335"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of pain during sexual intercourse and associated lower abdominal pain. She has no other symptoms. She recently changed her sexual partner and uses a copper intrauterine device (IUD) for contraception. She had a clear cervical screening test six months ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is lower abdominal and cervical tenderness, and cervicitis is seen on speculum examination. A urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin-clavulanate and review in one week","Remove copper IUD","Diagnostic laparoscopy","Ceftriaxone, doxycycline and metronidazole with review in 48 hours","Pelvic ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), an infection of the upper female genital tract. The diagnosis is based on clinical findings including lower abdominal pain, dyspareunia (pain during intercourse), cervical motion tenderness, and cervicitis. Recent change in sexual partner increases the risk of sexually transmitted infections, which are common causes of PID.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step is to initiate empiric antibiotic therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone, doxycycline and metronidazole with review in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct option. This regimen covers the most common causative organisms: \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E (ceftriaxone), \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E (doxycycline), and anaerobic bacteria (metronidazole). Early review is crucial to assess treatment response and adjust therapy if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for PID treatment as it does not provide sufficient coverage for \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EC. trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E. Additionally, a one-week review is too late for assessing treatment response in PID.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving the copper IUD\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the first step in management. While IUDs can increase the risk of PID, removal is only considered if there\u0027s no improvement after 48-72 hours of antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure and is not indicated as the initial management for uncomplicated PID. It may be considered in severe cases or when the diagnosis is uncertain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not the first-line investigation for PID. While it can help exclude other diagnoses or identify complications like tubo-ovarian abscess, the diagnosis of PID is primarily clinical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic therapy, management should include screening for sexually transmitted infections, partner notification and treatment, and counseling on safe sex practices. The patient should be advised to abstain from sexual intercourse until treatment is completed and symptoms have resolved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) should be suspected in sexually active women presenting with lower abdominal pain, dyspareunia, adnexal tenderness, cervical motion tenderness, and cervicitis.","Empiric antibiotic therapy covering Neisseria gonorrhoeae, Chlamydia trachomatis, and anaerobes is the first-line treatment for Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), with early follow-up to assess response."],"references":["Pelvic inflammatory diseases (PID). In: Australian STI management guidelines [online]. 2024. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/syndromes/pelvic-inflammatory-diseases-pid/","Curry A, Williams T, Penny ML. Pelvic Inflammatory Disease: Diagnosis, Management, and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019;100:357-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31524362/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39843"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39843"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T09:35:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T09:37:12+09:30","number":21,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-10-04T09:36:31+09:30","plagiarismScore":22,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4080-21.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T025007Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=4bb51673504e23cab7cf15515adef705f0dd7ac85781d0eb195e6abdcfbabf96"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4080"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54335"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi